# Envoy HTTP Request Routing: Complete Path Investigation

**Repository:** envoyproxy/envoy  
**Scope:** Full trace from TCP `accept()` syscall through filter chain processing, route resolution, upstream cluster selection, connection establishment, and response return.

---

## Table of Contents

1. [Architecture Overview](#1-architecture-overview)
2. [Layer 1 — TCP Accept](#2-layer-1--tcp-accept)
3. [Layer 2 — Listener Filter Chain](#3-layer-2--listener-filter-chain)
4. [Layer 3 — Filter Chain Selection](#4-layer-3--filter-chain-selection)
5. [Layer 4 — Network Filter Chain and HCM Initialization](#5-layer-4--network-filter-chain-and-hcm-initialization)
6. [Layer 5 — HTTP Codec and Stream Creation](#6-layer-5--http-codec-and-stream-creation)
7. [Layer 6 — HTTP Filter Manager: Decode Path](#7-layer-6--http-filter-manager-decode-path)
8. [Layer 7 — Route Resolution](#8-layer-7--route-resolution)
9. [Layer 8 — Router Filter: Cluster Selection and Connection Pool](#9-layer-8--router-filter-cluster-selection-and-connection-pool)
10. [Layer 9 — Connection Pool](#10-layer-9--connection-pool)
11. [Layer 10 — Upstream Connection Establishment](#11-layer-10--upstream-connection-establishment)
12. [Layer 11 — Response Path](#12-layer-11--response-path)
13. [Complete Call Chain Summary](#13-complete-call-chain-summary)
14. [Key Data Structures and Interfaces](#14-key-data-structures-and-interfaces)

---

## 1. Architecture Overview

Envoy processes HTTP requests through a layered pipeline. Each layer is strictly separated by interface boundaries, enabling independent extensibility. The full downstream-to-upstream path traverses:

```
Kernel TCP stack
  └─ TcpListenerImpl          (libevent socket read event)
       └─ ActiveTcpListener   (per-listener accept logic, connection balancing)
            └─ ActiveTcpSocket (listener filter chain iteration)
                 └─ FilterChainManagerImpl (filter chain matching)
                      └─ ConnectionManagerImpl / HCM (HTTP codec, stream lifecycle)
                           └─ FilterManager (HTTP decoder filter chain)
                                └─ Router::Filter (route lookup, cluster selection)
                                     └─ ConnPoolImplBase (connection pool)
                                          └─ ClientConnectionImpl (TCP connect)
                                               └─ TransportSocket (TLS handshake)
```

All I/O runs on worker threads via libevent. Each worker thread owns its own dispatcher, connection pool maps, and thread-local cluster snapshots.

---

## 2. Layer 1 — TCP Accept

**File:** `source/common/network/tcp_listener_impl.cc`

### Event Registration

```cpp
// TcpListenerImpl constructor (L128–L152)
socket_->ioHandle().initializeFileEvent(
    dispatcher,
    [this](uint32_t events) { return onSocketEvent(events); },
    Event::FileTriggerType::Level,   // level-triggered to avoid missed events
    Event::FileReadyType::Read);
```

The listener socket is registered with libevent in **level-triggered** mode. Level-triggered is chosen deliberately: edge-triggered mode could miss connections if `accept()` returns `EAGAIN` mid-loop or if the loop is capped early.

### `onSocketEvent()` — L56

```cpp
absl::Status TcpListenerImpl::onSocketEvent(short flags) {
  uint32_t connections_accepted_from_kernel_count = 0;
  for (; connections_accepted_from_kernel_count < max_connections_to_accept_per_socket_event_;
       ++connections_accepted_from_kernel_count) {

    IoHandlePtr io_handle =
        socket_->ioHandle().accept(reinterpret_cast<sockaddr*>(&remote_addr), &remote_addr_len);
    if (io_handle == nullptr) {
      break;  // EAGAIN — kernel queue drained
    }

    if (rejectCxOverGlobalLimit()) {
      io_handle->close();
      cb_.onReject(TcpListenerCallbacks::RejectCause::GlobalCxLimit);
      continue;
    } else if (listener_accept_ != nullptr && listener_accept_->shouldShedLoad()) {
      io_handle->close();
      cb_.onReject(TcpListenerCallbacks::RejectCause::OverloadAction);
      continue;
    }

    cb_.onAccept(std::make_unique<AcceptedSocketImpl>(
        std::move(io_handle), local_address, remote_address, ...));
  }
}
```

**Key behaviors:**
- Loops up to `max_connections_to_accept_per_socket_event_` times per event to amortize event overhead.
- Breaks on `nullptr` return from `accept()` (maps to `EAGAIN`/`EWOULDBLOCK`).
- Calls `rejectCxOverGlobalLimit()` (L21) before handing off each socket.

### `rejectCxOverGlobalLimit()` — L21

Two enforcement modes depending on configuration:

| Mode | Mechanism |
|------|-----------|
| Overload manager enabled | `overload_state_->tryAllocateResource(GlobalDownstreamMaxConnections, 1)` — atomic resource allocation |
| Runtime key mode | `AcceptedSocketImpl::acceptedSocketCount() >= global_cx_limit` — global atomic counter |

After passing both checks, `cb_.onAccept()` fires. `cb_` is the `ActiveTcpListener` for this listener.

---

## 3. Layer 2 — Listener Filter Chain

**Files:**  
- `source/common/listener_manager/active_tcp_listener.cc`  
- `source/common/listener_manager/active_tcp_socket.cc`  
- `source/common/listener_manager/active_stream_listener_base.h`

### `ActiveTcpListener::onAccept()` — L80

```cpp
void ActiveTcpListener::onAccept(Network::ConnectionSocketPtr&& socket) {
  if (listenerConnectionLimitReached()) {
    socket->close();
    stats_.downstream_cx_overflow_.inc();
    return;
  }
  onAcceptWorker(std::move(socket), config_->handOffRestoredDestinationConnections(), false);
}
```

Per-listener connection limit is checked here (separate from the global limit checked in `TcpListenerImpl`).

### `ActiveTcpListener::onAcceptWorker()` — L108

```cpp
void ActiveTcpListener::onAcceptWorker(Network::ConnectionSocketPtr&& socket,
                                       bool hand_off_restored_destination_connections,
                                       bool rebalanced) {
  // Capture TCP RTT before any processing
  absl::optional<std::chrono::milliseconds> t = socket->lastRoundTripTime();
  if (t.has_value()) {
    socket->connectionInfoProvider().setRoundTripTime(t.value());
  }

  if (!rebalanced) {
    Network::BalancedConnectionHandler& target_handler =
        connection_balancer_.pickTargetHandler(*this);
    if (&target_handler != this) {
      target_handler.post(std::move(socket));  // cross-thread rebalance
      return;
    }
  }

  auto active_socket = std::make_unique<ActiveTcpSocket>(
      *this, std::move(socket), hand_off_restored_destination_connections);
  onSocketAccepted(std::move(active_socket));
}
```

**Connection balancing:** If a `ConnectionBalancer` is configured (e.g., exact balance), the connection may be posted to a different worker thread's dispatcher via `target_handler.post()`. This is the mechanism for even connection distribution across workers.

### `onSocketAccepted()` — `active_stream_listener_base.h` L85

```cpp
void onSocketAccepted(std::unique_ptr<ActiveTcpSocket> active_socket) {
  // Instantiate listener filters and begin iteration
  if (config_->filterChainFactory().createListenerFilterChain(*active_socket)) {
    active_socket->startFilterChain();
  } else {
    active_socket->socket().close();
    return;
  }

  if (!active_socket->isEndFilterIteration()) {
    active_socket->startTimer();  // listener filter timeout
    LinkedList::moveIntoListBack(std::move(active_socket), sockets_);
  }
}
```

`createListenerFilterChain()` instantiates listener filters (e.g., TLS Inspector, HTTP Inspector, Proxy Protocol) and adds them to `active_socket->accept_filters_`. `startFilterChain()` is an alias for `continueFilterChain(true)`.

### `ActiveTcpSocket::continueFilterChain()` — L111

```cpp
void ActiveTcpSocket::continueFilterChain(bool success) {
  if (success) {
    // Advance iterator; on first call iter_ == end(), so it resets to begin()
    if (iter_ == accept_filters_.end()) {
      iter_ = accept_filters_.begin();
    } else {
      iter_ = std::next(iter_);
    }

    for (; iter_ != accept_filters_.end(); iter_++) {
      Network::FilterStatus status = (*iter_)->onAccept(*this);
      if (status == Network::FilterStatus::StopIteration) {
        // Filter needs more data (e.g., TLS Inspector peeking bytes)
        if (listener_filter_buffer_ == nullptr) {
          createListenerFilterBuffer();
        }
        if ((*iter_)->maxReadBytes() > 0) {
          listener_filter_buffer_->disableOnDataCallback(false);
          listener_filter_buffer_->activateFileEvent(Event::FileReadyType::Read);
        }
        return;  // resume later via ListenerFilterBuffer callback
      }
    }
    // All filters passed
    newConnection();
  }
}
```

**Listener filter data peeking:** When a filter like TLS Inspector returns `StopIteration`, a `ListenerFilterBufferImpl` is created. This buffer peeks bytes from the socket (without consuming them) and calls the filter's `onData()` callback when enough bytes are available. The filter then sets socket metadata (e.g., `detectedTransportProtocol = "tls"`, `requestedServerName`) and calls `continueFilterChain(true)` to resume.

### `ActiveTcpSocket::newConnection()` — L185

```cpp
void ActiveTcpSocket::newConnection() {
  connected_ = true;

  // Optional: redirect to another listener (iptables TPROXY / original destination)
  if (hand_off_restored_destination_connections_ &&
      socket_->connectionInfoProvider().localAddressRestored()) {
    new_listener = listener_.getBalancedHandlerByAddress(
        *socket_->connectionInfoProvider().localAddress());
  }

  if (new_listener.has_value()) {
    listener_.decNumConnections();
    new_listener.value().get().onAcceptWorker(std::move(socket_), false, false);
  } else {
    // Set default transport protocol if no listener filter set it
    if (socket_->detectedTransportProtocol().empty()) {
      socket_->setDetectedTransportProtocol("raw_buffer");
    }
    listener_.newConnection(std::move(socket_), std::move(stream_info_));
  }
}
```

---

## 4. Layer 3 — Filter Chain Selection

**File:** `source/common/listener_manager/filter_chain_manager_impl.cc`

### `ActiveStreamListenerBase::newConnection()` — L38

```cpp
void ActiveStreamListenerBase::newConnection(Network::ConnectionSocketPtr&& socket,
                                             std::unique_ptr<StreamInfo::StreamInfo> stream_info) {
  const auto filter_chain =
      config_->filterChainManager().findFilterChain(*socket, *stream_info);
  if (filter_chain == nullptr) {
    stats_.no_filter_chain_match_.inc();
    socket->close();
    return;
  }

  socket->connectionInfoProvider().setListenerInfo(config_->listenerInfo());
  socket->connectionInfoProvider().setFilterChainInfo(
      std::make_shared<FilterChainInfoImpl>(filter_chain->name()));

  auto transport_socket = filter_chain->transportSocketFactory().createDownstreamTransportSocket();
  auto server_conn_ptr = dispatcher().createServerConnection(
      std::move(socket), std::move(transport_socket), *stream_info);

  const bool empty_filter_chain = !config_->filterChainFactory().createNetworkFilterChain(
      *server_conn_ptr, filter_chain->networkFilterFactories());
  if (empty_filter_chain) {
    server_conn_ptr->close(Network::ConnectionCloseType::NoFlush, "no_filters");
  }
  newActiveConnection(*filter_chain, std::move(server_conn_ptr), std::move(stream_info));
}
```

### `FilterChainManagerImpl::findFilterChain()` — L514

The filter chain manager implements a **multi-level trie/map lookup** with the following precedence order (most specific wins):

```
1. Destination port  (exact match, then catch-all port 0)
2. Destination IP    (LcTrie CIDR match)
3. Server name       (exact → wildcard suffix → catch-all "")
4. Transport protocol (exact → catch-all "")
5. Application protocol (ALPN exact → catch-all "")
6. Direct source IP  (LcTrie CIDR match)
7. Source type       (SAME_IP_OR_LOOPBACK → EXTERNAL → ANY)
8. Source IP         (LcTrie CIDR match)
9. Source port       (exact → catch-all port 0)
```

**Implementation detail — each level delegates to the next:**

```cpp
// L563: Destination IP via LcTrie
findFilterChainForDestinationIP(destination_ips_trie, socket)
  → findFilterChainForServerName(server_names_map, socket)       // L580
    → findFilterChainForTransportProtocol(transport_protocols_map, socket)  // L611
      → findFilterChainForApplicationProtocols(app_protocols_map, socket)   // L631
        → findFilterChainForDirectSourceIP(direct_source_ips_trie, socket)  // L651
          → findFilterChainForSourceTypes(source_types_array, socket)       // L668
            → findFilterChainForSourceIpAndPort(source_ips_trie, socket)    // L702
```

**Server name wildcard matching (L592–L606):**
```cpp
// Exact: "www.example.com"
// Wildcard suffix: ".example.com", ".com" (longest match wins)
size_t pos = server_name.find('.', 1);
while (pos < server_name.size() - 1 && pos != std::string::npos) {
  const std::string wildcard = server_name.substr(pos);  // ".example.com"
  const auto match = server_names_map.find(wildcard);
  if (match != server_names_map.end()) return ...;
  pos = server_name.find('.', pos + 1);
}
```

**Alternative path — xDS matcher (L516–L560):**  
If `matcher_` is set (unified matcher API), `findFilterChainUsingMatcher()` is called instead, which evaluates a `Matcher::MatchTree<Network::MatchingData>` against socket attributes and dynamic metadata.

---

## 5. Layer 4 — Network Filter Chain and HCM Initialization

**File:** `source/common/listener_manager/active_stream_listener_base.cc` (continued from L68)

After `findFilterChain()` returns a matched chain:

1. `filter_chain->transportSocketFactory().createDownstreamTransportSocket()` — creates the transport socket (e.g., `SslSocket` wrapping BoringSSL for TLS, or `RawBufferSocket` for plaintext).
2. `dispatcher().createServerConnection(socket, transport_socket, stream_info)` — wraps the raw fd in a `ServerConnectionImpl`.
3. `config_->filterChainFactory().createNetworkFilterChain(*server_conn_ptr, filter_chain->networkFilterFactories())` — instantiates network filters. For HTTP traffic this creates `ConnectionManagerImpl` as a `Network::ReadFilter`.
4. `newActiveConnection()` — moves the connection into `ActiveTcpConnection`, sets `TCP_NODELAY`, increments stats, registers connection callbacks.

### HCM as a Network Filter

`ConnectionManagerImpl` implements `Network::ReadFilter`:

```cpp
// Called once when connection is established
Network::FilterStatus ConnectionManagerImpl::onNewConnection() {
  if (!read_callbacks_->connection().streamInfo().protocol()) {
    // Non-QUIC: continue to next network filter (none typically)
    return Network::FilterStatus::Continue;
  }
  // QUIC: codec already known, create immediately
  Buffer::OwnedImpl dummy;
  createCodec(dummy);
  return Network::FilterStatus::StopIteration;
}

// Called for each read event with accumulated data
Network::FilterStatus ConnectionManagerImpl::onData(Buffer::Instance& data, bool) {
  if (!codec_) {
    createCodec(data);  // lazy codec creation on first bytes
  }
  do {
    const Status status = codec_->dispatch(data);
    // handle errors...
  } while (redispatch);
  return Network::FilterStatus::StopIteration;
}
```

`createCodec()` (L465) calls `config_->createCodec()` which inspects the first bytes to determine HTTP/1.x vs HTTP/2 (via ALPN or the HTTP/2 preface `PRI * HTTP/2.0\r\n\r\nSM\r\n\r\n`).

---

## 6. Layer 5 — HTTP Codec and Stream Creation

**File:** `source/common/http/conn_manager_impl.cc`

### Codec Dispatch

`codec_->dispatch(data)` parses the incoming byte stream. When a complete set of request headers is parsed, the codec calls back into HCM:

```cpp
// Called by codec when a new HTTP stream is detected
RequestDecoder& ConnectionManagerImpl::newStream(ResponseEncoder& response_encoder,
                                                 bool is_internally_created) {
  // Disable connection idle timer while stream is active
  if (connection_idle_timer_) {
    connection_idle_timer_->disableTimer();
  }

  // Create buffer memory account for flow control / watermark tracking
  auto& buffer_factory = dispatcher_->getWatermarkFactory();
  auto downstream_stream_account = buffer_factory.createAccount(response_encoder.getStream());

  auto new_stream = std::make_unique<ActiveStream>(
      *this, response_encoder.getStream().bufferLimit(),
      std::move(downstream_stream_account));

  // Check max requests per connection (HTTP/1.1 drain, HTTP/2 GOAWAY)
  accumulated_requests_++;
  if (config_->maxRequestsPerConnection() > 0 &&
      accumulated_requests_ >= config_->maxRequestsPerConnection()) {
    if (codec_->protocol() < Protocol::Http2) {
      new_stream->filter_manager_.streamInfo().setShouldDrainConnectionUponCompletion(true);
    } else if (drain_state_ == DrainState::NotDraining) {
      startDrainSequence();  // sends GOAWAY
    }
  }

  new_stream->response_encoder_ = &response_encoder;
  new_stream->response_encoder_->getStream().addCallbacks(*new_stream);
  LinkedList::moveIntoList(std::move(new_stream), streams_);
  return **streams_.begin();
}
```

The returned `RequestDecoder&` is the `ActiveStream`. The codec calls `decodeHeaders()` on it next.

### `ActiveStream::decodeHeaders()` — L1193

This is the central request processing entry point. Key steps in order:

```
1.  Record last downstream header byte received timestamp (L1200)
2.  Validate headers (L1227): method, host, path, scheme, content-length consistency
3.  Snap route config (L1232–1244):
      - RDS: snapped_route_config_ = routeConfigProvider()->configCast()
      - SRDS: snapScopedRouteConfig() → snapped_route_config_ per scope key
4.  Overload check (L1247): shed load if overload manager signals
5.  Handle Expect: 100-continue (L1270): send 100 immediately, strip header
6.  Validate Host header presence (L1287)
7.  Path normalization (L1335): maybeNormalizePath() — redirect or reject on traversal
8.  mutateRequestHeaders() (L1372): XFF processing, IP detection, trusted proxy handling
9.  refreshCachedRoute() (L1392): initial route lookup
10. createDownstreamFilterChain() (L1403): instantiate HTTP filters from route/vhost config
11. traceRequest() (L1434): initialize distributed tracing span
12. filter_manager_.decodeHeaders(*request_headers_, end_stream) (L1439)
```

**`refreshCachedRoute()` — L1678:**
```cpp
void ConnectionManagerImpl::ActiveStream::refreshCachedRoute(const Router::RouteCallback& cb) {
  if (routeCacheBlocked()) return;

  Router::RouteConstSharedPtr route;
  if (request_headers_ != nullptr) {
    if (config_->isRoutable() && config_->scopedRouteConfigProvider() != nullptr) {
      snapScopedRouteConfig();  // re-select scope if scope key header changed
    }
    if (snapped_route_config_ != nullptr) {
      route = snapped_route_config_->route(cb, *request_headers_,
                                           filter_manager_.streamInfo(), stream_id_);
    }
  }
  setRoute(std::move(route));
}
```

The route is cached in `cached_route_` and can be refreshed by filters that mutate headers (e.g., header-based routing filters).

---

## 7. Layer 6 — HTTP Filter Manager: Decode Path

**File:** `source/common/http/filter_manager.cc`

### `FilterManager::decodeHeaders()` — L537

```cpp
void FilterManager::decodeHeaders(ActiveStreamDecoderFilter* filter,
                                  RequestHeaderMap& headers, bool end_stream) {
  StreamDecoderFilters::Iterator entry =
      commonDecodePrefix(filter, FilterIterationStartState::AlwaysStartFromNext);

  for (; entry != decoder_filters_.end(); entry++) {
    state_.filter_call_state_ |= FilterCallState::DecodeHeaders;
    (*entry)->end_stream_ = (end_stream && continue_data_entry == decoder_filters_.end());

    FilterHeadersStatus status = (*entry)->decodeHeaders(headers, (*entry)->end_stream_);

    state_.filter_call_state_ &= ~FilterCallState::DecodeHeaders;

    const auto continue_iteration =
        (*entry)->commonHandleAfterHeadersCallback(status, end_stream);

    if (!continue_iteration && std::next(entry) != decoder_filters_.end()) {
      maybeContinueDecoding(continue_data_entry);
      return;  // filter stopped iteration; resume later via continueDecoding()
    }
  }
}
```

**Filter status semantics:**

| `FilterHeadersStatus` | Behavior |
|----------------------|----------|
| `Continue` | Advance to next filter immediately |
| `StopIteration` | Pause; filter must call `continueDecoding()` later |
| `StopAllIterationAndBuffer` | Pause all; buffer body; resume on `continueDecoding()` |
| `StopAllIterationAndWatermark` | Pause all; apply watermark; resume on `continueDecoding()` |
| `ContinueAndDontEndStream` | Continue but suppress `end_stream` flag (filter injected body) |

Decoder filters are stored in `decoder_filters_` in **forward order** (A→B→C). Encoder filters in `encoder_filters_` are iterated in **reverse order** (C→B→A) during response encoding.

The terminal decoder filter is always the **Router filter** (`Router::Filter`), which is the last entry in `decoder_filters_`.

---

## 8. Layer 7 — Route Resolution

**File:** `source/common/router/config_impl.cc`

Route resolution is triggered by `snapped_route_config_->route(cb, headers, stream_info, stream_id)`.

### `ConfigImpl::route()` — L2450 → `RouteMatcher::route()` — L2299

```cpp
RouteConstSharedPtr RouteMatcher::route(const RouteCallback& cb,
